    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Collation:  Paper, 140 leaves; 1&#xB9;&#x2070; (leaf 1 front pastedown) 2-3&#xB9;&#xB2; 4&#xB9;&#x2070; 5-9&#xB9;&#xB2; 10&#xB9;&#x2074;&#x207A;&#xB9; (leaf 9 is singleton) 11&#xB9;&#xB2; 12&#xB9;&#xB2;&#x207B;1 (leaf 11 end pastedown, missing leaf 12); modern foliation in pencil, [1-140], upper right recto.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Layout:  Ruled in 5 columns in faint red ink, one narrow column for dates on the left, a wide center column for notes, and three narrow columns on the right for amounts in pounds, shillings, and pence; quarto format.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Script: Written in cursive script in the hand of Anne Doughty.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Binding:  Contemporary (18th-century) vellum; blind-tooled borders on covers.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Origin: Written in London (f. 21v); Tunbridge (f. 39r); Lilford Hall, Northamptonshire (f. 45r); Henley (f. 45r) between 1767 and 1772 (f. 2v-56r) and in Hanworth Hall, Norfolk (f. 57v); and London (f. 59r) between 1776 and 1787,</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Expenses for food and drink; household items such as soap, candles, and charcoal; household equipment such as dishes, decanters, pudding pans, and a carpet broom; services such as washing and transportation; and wages for servants.  These are recorded at the item level chronologically from 1767 to 1772 and again in 1776 (f. 2v-64r).  Starting in 1777, expenses are recorded at the level of  bills paid to vendors, grouped by category, with sections, often starting on new pages, for butter, eggs, fish, poultry, charwomen, house, rabbits, lemons, baker, fishmonger, greengrocer, oil man, tallow chandler, washing, brewer, milk and cream, coal merchant, confectioner, and servants' journey (f. 64v-134r).  The last pages of the volume are used for records of wages and include repeated signatures by women servants to acknowledge receipt of wages.between 1776 and 1785 (f. 134v-140r), with one receipt from 1794 noted on the last page (f. 140r).</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="524">
  <marc:subfield code="a">UPenn Ms. Codex 2025.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1="0" ind2=" " tag="545">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Daughter of Thomas Powys of Lilford Hall (last signing the records as Anne Powys, f. 51v), married Robert Lee Doughty of Hanford Hall in 1777 (receipts written to Mrs. Doughty, f. 111r-112r, 136r-140r).</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1="1" ind2=" " tag="561">
